[[File:Evolution of SPC Forecasts Leading to March 6, 2017.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Progression of a well-anticipated extremely critical event across the Central Plains on March 6, 2017. This event produced wildfires that burned 1,200,000 acres of land, and killed seven people.]]
An extremely critical fire weather event is the greatest threat level issued by the [[National Weather Service|NWS]] [[Storm Prediction Center]] (SPC) for [[wildfire]] events in the [[United States]]. Extremely critical areas are issued only several times a year when forecasters at the SPC are confident of extremely dangerous wildfire conditions on a given day. These are typically reserved for the most extreme events.<ref>{{cite web |title = National Digital Forecast Database (NDFD) Fire Weather Outlook Elements NWS Product Description Document (PDD) |work = SPC and its Products |publisher = Storm Prediction Center |date = 2012-03-26 |url = http://products.weather.gov/PDD/ndfdSPCfire.pdf |accessdate = }}</ref> 

Fire weather products have been issued by the Storm Prediction Center since 1998;<ref name="SPC Fire Weather Product - July 28, 2001">{{cite web |title = Storm Prediction Center's Fire Weather Verification Case Study 3: July 28–29 |publisher = Storm Prediction Center |url = https://ams.confex.com/ams/pdfpapers/25559.pdf |accessdate = 2013-06-30 }}</ref> however, there is very little online documentation for days before 2002 due to the lack of [[Storm Prediction Center#Fire weather products|SPC archives]].<ref name="SPC Fire Weather OutlookFire Weather Outlooks Archives">{{cite web|last1=Cohen|first1=Ariel|title=Fire Weather Outlooks Archive and Links|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/fire_wx/overview.html|website=Storm Prediction Center|accessdate=12 February 2017}}</ref> Therefore, it is likely that there were additional extremely critical days with no online documentation. 

