{{Infobox ecoregion |name = Southeast Tibet shrub and meadows |image = Southeast Tibet meadows.jpg |image_size = |image_alt = |caption = Flowering summer meadows in [[Luqu County]] in the eastern Tibetan Pleateau |map = |map_size = |map_alt = |map_caption = |biogeographic_realm = [[Palearctic]] |biome = [[Montane Grasslands and Shrublands]] |animals = |bird_species = |mammal_species = |border = |borders = |area = |country = [[China]] |countries = |state = |region_type = |elevation = |coordinates = |geology = |seas = |rivers = |climate = |soil = |conservation = |global200 = |habitat_loss = |habitat_loss_ref = |protected = |protected_ref = }} The '''Southeast Tibet shrub and meadows''' are a [[montane grassland]] [[ecoregion]] that cover the southeast and eastern parts of the [[Tibetan Plateau]] in [[China]]. The meadows in this region of [[Tibet]] are in the path of the [[monsoon]] rains and are wetter than the other upland areas of the Tibetan Plateau. Chinese [[provinces of China|provinces]] covered by the Southeast Tibet shrub and meadows include the alpine parts of eastern [[Tibet Autonomous Region]], the alpine parts of western and northern [[Sichuan]], extreme southern and eastern [[Qinghai]], and the montane areas of southern [[Gansu]]. Many mountain ranges support the Southeast Tibet meadows, stretching from the [[Nyainqêntanglha Mountains]] in the southwest to the [[Qilian Mountains]] in the northeast.<ref name="species">{{cite web|title=Southeast Tibet shrub and meadows|url=http://www.globalspecies.org/ecoregions/display/PA1017|website=Global Species|publisher=Myers Enterprises II|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>
Influenced by the Asian monsoon, he Southeast Tibet shrub and meadows experience seasonal climatic variation. Dry conditions in the winter lead to primarily brown landscapes, but summer rains revitalize grasses and turn the landscapes green. To the northwest, the meadows transition to the drier [[Tibetan Plateau alpine shrub and meadows]].
Human activity is fairly high as the Southeast Tibet shrub and meadows provide grazing areas for domestic animals such as [[yak]]. While not well suited for most agriculture, [[Pastoralism|pastoralist]] [[Tibetan people]] live across the region.<ref name="species" /> The northeastern part of this ecoregion was traditionally known as [[Amdo]] to Tibetans, while the southwestern part made up the higher elevation portions of [[Kham]].
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Palearctic ecoregions]] [[Category:Montane grasslands and shrublands]] [[Category:Ecoregions of China]]
{{ecoregion-stub}}

{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}
A '''volcanic block''' is a fragment of [[rock (geology)|rock]] that measures more than {{Convert|64|mm|in|abbr=on}} in diameter and is erupted in a solid condition. 

Blocks are formed from material from previous eruptions or from [[Country rock (geology)|country rock]] and are therefore mostly accessory or accidental in origin. Blocks also occur due to the impact and breakage of [[volcanic bombs]] (a bomb is a block with streamlined appearance, often expelled in a molten state). Bombs can also occur due to the disruption of the crust of a lava dome that has formed up or over a vent during an eruption. 

==Features==
Blocks are nearly always angular to sub-angular and roughly equidimensional. If the parent rock is flow-foliated lava, sedimentary material or [[schistose]] metamorphic rocks, the blocks may have a plate-like or slab-like form. In other cases, blocks derived from great depths may resemble polished water-worn pebbles and are cobbled due to fluidisation and upwards transport.

Blocks can be enormous and may be transported great distances from the [[volcanic vent]]. The 1924 eruption of [[Kīlauea]], [[Hawaii]], expelled rocks weighing up to 14 tons; and Mount [[Vesuvius]] in [[Italy]] discharged blocks weighing 2-3 tons over distances of 100-200m.

